channel.title: Interleaved RSS Feed
channel.description: This is an interleaved feed of the most recent entries from each RSS source, skipping any feeds with errors.

item.title: Nvidia’s Jensen Huang plays down competition worries as key supplier disappoints with subdued expectations for AI chip sales
item.description: Hype for AI is so feverish that even meeting expectations isn't enough for investors.

item.title: Specter of Putin casts a shadow over the Trump-Biden debate
item.description: Russian leader Vladimir Putin was invoked roughly a dozen times in the 90-minute debate between President Joe Biden and former President Donald Trump.

item.title: Live blog: Biden, Trump spar over inflation, tax cuts

item.description: Blame the U.S. and its export controls blocking AI chip sales to China.

item.title: Fed and European Central Bank could cut interest rates in September, Morgan Stanley strategist says
item.description: The U.S. Federal Reserve and European Central Bank could move to cut rates in September, a Morgan Stanley strategist said Friday.

item.description: With Biden having already secured a presumptive nomination, Democrats’ prospects for a course change are diminishing.

item.title: Friday's analyst calls: Solar stock gets a price target increase, Nike downgrades after earnings

item.title: SoftBank shares rise on $1.86 billion debt offering as CEO talks up 'super' AI
item.description: Softbank, which has a huge technology investment arm called the Vision Fund, has suggested it is looking to ramp up investments in artificial intelligence.

item.title: The big winner of the Biden-Trump debate? Your neighborhood bar.
CEO of cosmetics giant L’Oreal announces slower growth as Chinese market flatlines
item.description: China had long been a growth engine for L’Oreal, with consumers snapping up its high-end cosmetics offerings.

item.title: Younger generations of Asians are spending big on art
item.description: More than 40% of Sotheby's contemporary art buyers in Asia are millennials. While the size of the global art market fell last year, sales in China were up 9%.
